## Getting Started

### Requirements

- Python 3.10+
- PyTorch (CUDA recommended)

### Install

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/nano-gpt.git
cd nano-gpt
pip install torch
```

### Download the dataset

```bash
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/karpathy/char-rnn/master/data/tinyshakespeare/input.txt
```

### Train

```bash
python train.py
```

Training takes ~5 minutes on an NVIDIA RTX 3060 Ti. Generated text is saved to `output.txt`.

## Key Concepts Implemented

- **Character-level tokenization** — each unique character maps to an integer, forming a vocabulary of 65 tokens
- **Token + positional embeddings** — learned representations for both token identity and sequence position, summed to encode "what" and "where"
- **Scaled dot-product attention** — queries and keys produce attention weights that determine how tokens share information, scaled by √(head_size) for training stability
- **Causal masking** — a lower-triangular mask prevents tokens from attending to future positions during training
- **Multi-head attention** — multiple attention heads run in parallel, each learning different patterns (e.g., tracking speaker, punctuation, word proximity), then combined via linear projection
- **Feedforward network** — a two-layer MLP (expand 4×, ReLU, compress) applied independently to each token after attention
- **Residual connections** — input is added to each sub-layer's output (`x = x + sublayer(x)`), enabling gradient flow through deep networks
- **Layer normalization** — normalizes activations to zero mean and unit variance before each sub-layer (pre-norm variant)
- **Dropout** — randomly zeroes activations during training to prevent overfitting

## What I Learned

- How self-attention enables tokens to dynamically select and aggregate context from earlier positions
- Why multi-head attention outperforms a single large head — independent projections discover diverse, complementary patterns
- The role of residual connections in enabling gradient flow through deep transformer stacks
- How layer normalization stabilizes training by keeping activations in a consistent range between blocks
- The relationship between model capacity, dataset size, and overfitting — tracked via train/val loss divergence
- End-to-end PyTorch workflow: custom `nn.Module` classes, training loops, gradient computation, and GPU acceleration

